gs":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":100,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Loudham was born about 1355, in Rempstone, Nottinghamshire, England, her father, John Loudham II, was 42 and her mother, Isabel Breton, was 32. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Thomas de Bekering. She died in Nottinghamshire, England."},"et":{"about 1355–":"umbes 1355–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1360–1403":"1360–1403","1365–1390":"1365–1390","–1352":"–1352","–Male":"Surnud","–1425":"–1425","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1386–Male":"1386–Surnud","–1432":"–1432","1314–1387":"1314–1387","1324–1376":"1324–1376","1352":"1352","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1425":"1425","1403":"1403","1314":"1314","1324":"1324","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","1387":"1387","1365":"1365","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","about 1355":"umbes 1355","about 1375":"umbes 1375","about 1386":"umbes 1386","26 May 1347":"26 mai 1347","Remps